Covid-19 in Sweden and India

Zihui Liu, Yuanchen Bai, Mengyan Wu

I. Introduction

The COVID-19 has claimed the lives of massive amount of people and posed negative influence on many aspect of people’s lives. In response to the epidemic, governments of different countries take various actions to cope with the situation. In particular,due to the strong contagious feature of this disease, much emphasis are lay on blocking the source of infection. Depending on policies and local conditions, they achieve distinct results.

In this project, we would like to evaluate the relation between government policy and the number of infection. Since government policies cover a wide range and some of their influences are long-term ones whose effects could not be easily observed, we mainly focus on the policies of people’s daily activity . The trending advice of “keeping social distancing” has become one of the most popular recommendations in many countries. As is suggested by some scholars, people’s restricted mobility to workplaces and other commonly traveled places could relief the rise of epidemic rise(Yilmazkuday, 2020).This kind of policy is expected to have a better outcome when government measures across the countries become more stringent as the outbreak gets spiked(Hale et.al., 2020).By studying the scale of daily interaction within a country, we could get a rough idea of the extent of closeness and the strictness of government policy.

In particular,we choose two representative countries to study: One is India, which is a country with dense population and whose government is known to exert a strict social distancing policy. The other is Sweden, whose government poses relatively loose constraints over social distancing. We obtain the mobility and policy stringency of these two countries, and make evaluations about how these factors affect their infection rate both separative and comparatively.
With this case study approach, we try to answer the following questions: 1. How are the stringency and mobility of these two countries distributed over time? 2.How is the strictness of their policy affecting the confirmed cases? 3.How is the relationships among governments’ initiatives amid coronavirus pandemic and people’s responses to keep them staying at home? In particular, how effective are these governments in acting against the epidemic? If the relation between government policy, mobility data and confirmed cases contradict what people generally expect, how to account for these differences? Studying this topic could guide governments to tailor their policy to local needs, and thus take control of the outbreak of COVID-19 to prevent further loss.

In the next several sections, we will first introduce the source of our datasets and make simple visualizations to get a general idea of them. Our project involves 3 type of dataset: one is the daily confirmed cases of ever country, another is the stringency index measuring the strictness of policy inside country over time, the last is the mobility index categorized by types of mobility. Then we would introduce several statistical methods we use to answer our questions. In the simulation and analysis section, we implement these methods. Four methods will be implemented. First we choose 190 countries and do a smoothing process to anaylze the density distribution of the stringency index at each state state of COVID-19 of them. Among them India has high stringency index since the confirmation of first few cases, and Swedish has a relatively stringency index. Then we would like to test the hypothesis that India have a lower level of mobility given the high stringency. We take these two countries and do bootstrap tests for two distributions on their stringency index and mobility index respectively. Then we do a independence test to prove that stringency index, mobility and confirmed cases are not independent. Then we do bootstrap methods to analyze the exact relation between stringency index and mobility. In the end, we draw some conclusions on the basis of our discovery and make some suggestions.

II. Data

II.1 Datasets introduction

Three datasets are used in this report. The main dataset is the Oxford Covid-19 Government Response Tracker (OxCGRT) and other data include “Google Mobility” and Covid-19 confirmed cases. In the main part of this report, we focus on two countries’ related data: India and Sweden. For the range of the data, we choose data from 2020.2.20 to 2021.2.20.

II.1.1 Oxford Covid-19 Government Response Tracker (OxCGRT)

The data are published by Oxford University. The datasets are fetched from ourworldindata.org. OxCGRT collects publicly available information on 23 indicators of government policy response to Covid-19. The indicators fall into four categories:containment and closure policies, economic policies, health system policies and vaccine policies.
In this report, we particularly focus on the stringency index which is calculated from all ordinal containment and closure policy indicators, plus an indicator recording public information campaigns which indicates the strictness of “lockdown style” policies that primarily restrict people’s behavior. (bsg.ox.ac.uk, 2021)
It needs to be pointed out that these indexes merely represent the corresponding policies’ quantities and strictness rather than a score to assess them.

II.1.2 Google Mobility

The data are published by Google and are fetched from the official websites. The dataset updates at a daily frequency and keep track of most countries’ people’s mobility data beginning from 15th Feb., 2020.

The places are divided into 5 categories: Recreation like pubs and theaters, Groceries and Pharmacies, Parks like the Public Garden, Transit Stations like subway transition and sea ports, Workspaces and Residential.
It needs to be pointed out that “groceries and Pharmacies” is a general term for “Essential Trips” and “Residential” does not include those people whose workplaces are in the home like babysitters. Also, all the data are relative values rather than absolute values. The baseline day is the median value from the 5 week period Jan 3 – Feb 6, 2020. And the baseline day represents a normal value for that day of the week (google, 2021). For example, all the baseline of Monday is the median of the five Mondays during the period.

II.1.3 Covid-19 Confirmed Cases Time Series Data

The data are published by the Johns Hopkins University Center for Systems Science and Engineering (JHU CSSE). The dataset is fetched from github official account of JHU CSSE.
The data is updated on a daily frequency.

III. Methods

III.1 Smoothing

III.2 Bootstrap

III.2.1 Stratified Bootstrap estimation of the difference of means

Since we have to make use of the data of two countries, we assume that these two samples are independent. \[X_{1},...,X_{n}\overset{\text{i.i.d}}{\sim} F\] \[Y_{1},...Y_{m}\overset{\text{i.i.d}}{\sim} G\] To get a rough idea of the data, we would like to compare the mean by calculating the difference of means (Fredrickson, 2021): \[\bigtriangleup=E(X)-E(Y)\] We’ll use the bootstrap method in the two sets of data separately to get estimates of means and then combine them. The statistic argument in boot function is the difference of mean of the two groups.
To deal with two groups of data, we have to combine them into a single dataset to do the bootstrap. One way to sort out one group from another is by using a flag indicator, with data from one set marked as “True” and the other marked as “False”.

III.2.2 Parametric Bootstrap (The residual is estimated using CLT method)

When we want to investigate on some important values of \(x\), we treat these values as fixed, and sampled a varying number of \(Y_i\) for each \(x\) value. We want to model this conditional distribution of \(Y \, | \, x\) as: \[Y \, | \, x = \beta_0 + \beta_1 x + \epsilon\] where \(\beta_1 = \frac{\text{Cov}(X,Y)}{\text{Var}(X)}\), \(\beta_0 = E(Y) - \beta_1 E(X)\), \(E(\epsilon) = 0\) and \(Var(\epsilon)\) is independent with \(x\).

Since the normal distribution has “light tails” and assumptions based on normality can be sensitive to outliers, we decide to model \(\epsilon\) with a scaled \(t\)-distribution with 4 degrees of freedom: \[\epsilon \sim \frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{2}} t(4) \Rightarrow \text{Var}(\epsilon) = \sigma^2\] (The \(\sqrt{2}\) scale the \(t\)-distribution to have a variance of 1.)

To get an estimate of the distribution of \(\hat \beta_1\), we first Estimate \(\beta_0\), \(\beta_1\), and \(\sigma\) using linear regression. For all the \(x_i\) in the sample, generate \(\hat y_i = \hat \beta_0 + \hat \beta_1 x_i\). For \(B\) replications, generate \(Y_i^* = \hat y_i + \epsilon_i*\), where \(\epsilon^* \sim \frac{\hat \sigma}{\sqrt{2}} t(4)\). For each replication, use linear regression to estimate \(\hat \beta_1^*\). Finally, use the \(\alpha/2\) and \(1 - \alpha/2\) quantiles of the bootstrap distribution to get the confidence intervals: \([2 \hat \beta_1 - \hat \beta_1^*(1 - \alpha/2), 2 \hat \beta_1 - \hat \beta_1^*(\alpha/2)]\)

III.2.3 Parametric Bootstrap (The residual is estimated using non-parametric method)

Instead of applying the CLT theorem and sampling from an assumed distribution for \(\epsilon\), we can draw a sample with replacement from \(\hat \epsilon_i\) and make \(Y_i^* = \hat y_i + \epsilon_i^*\)

III.3 Permutation Test of Independence

To understand the relation of government policy on mobility and condition of the pandemic, we have to first test whether the three sets of data we found in the data section are inner related. Therefore, we need to do some independence tests.
Suppose we have a single sample of pairs \[(W_{i},Z_{i}),i=1,...,n,IID.\] Under the hypothesis that \(F_{WZ}=F_{W}F_{Z}\) holds when they are independent, we could arbitrarily permute all the Z values and any statistic \(T(W,Z)\) would have the same distribution. We could test this hypothesis with a test statistic for pairs(Fredrickson, 2021). In this case,we sample the correlation of the pair elements. If the p-value we get for this test is very small, we then could reject the hypothesis that the pair of variables are independent at some confidence level.
(Reference: STAT4060J Homework 5)

II.4 Stochastic processes based on SIR model

An important thing we notice which is inspired by Hsiang et al.(2020) is that there exists some stochastic processes that we can further explore. And instead of focusing on the mechanism of disease transmission and make assumptions on uncertain epepidemiological parameters, we can do something directly relating interventions to the change of confirmed cases. In this paper, we will explore “how the Stringency Index affects growth rate of confirmed cases.”

According to SIR model: \[I(t) = I(0)e^{gt}\] where \(I(0)\) is the number of infections at the start of the process, \(e\) is the Naperian base and \(g\) is the growth rate of infections at each unit of time.

Then if we choose two time points \(t_1\) and \(t_2\) and calculate the natural logarithm difference which represents the relative growth rate, we can show that the growth rate of infections is equal to the difference of two principal parameters defined in SIR model: transmission rate \(\phi\) and recovery rate \(\gamma\): \[log(I(t_1))-log(I(t_2)) = g = \phi - \gamma.\] It is reasonable to assume that \(\phi\) is time-invariant except that some policies like the lockdown or other restrictions and suggestions on people’s behavior are put forward. And the recovery rate also does not change much because of very short-run investments on the health system. Thus, the growth rate of the infection cases can be described as a function to policies affecting people’s behavior: \[\Delta log(I(t)) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 P(t) + u(t)\] where \(\beta_0\) is the growth rate of confirmed cases in the absence of those policies, \(\beta_1\) is the expected impact of the Stringency Index (\(P(t)\)) and \(u(t)\) is an error term.

To estimate \(\beta_1\), we will use four methods based on the checking of assumptions: Linear Regression, Non-Parametric Bootstrap and 2 Parametric Bootstraps. Details will be illustrated in the process of Simulation and Analysis Part.

IV.2 Bootstrap Test of mean on two samples on Stringency and Mobility Index of Sweden and India

We extract the recreation and residential index of Sweden and India, and combined them with the confirmed number of cases and stringency index from 2020.2.20 to 2021.2.20 respectively.We would like to compare the distribution of stringency index, recreation index and residential index of these two countries. Our hypothesis is: Sweden and India have different means of stringency index, movability index including recreation and residential index. To be specific, the null hypothesis are:India has a higher mean stingency index than Sweden, a larger mean recreation index than Sweden, and a larger mean residential index than Sweden.
To do this, we add a label of country_TF. Swedish data will have a country_TF=FALSE, while Indian data will have country_TF=TRUE.

First, we test the mean of stringency index for Sweden and India.

IV.3 Permutation Test of Independence

As we have observed in the visualization part, recreational index and residential factor may be influenced by the government policy, and the policy could further influence the condition of the pandemic. Then we would like to explore the possible relationship between government policy, population mobility and confirmed number of people. If there exist correlation between each pair of factors, we could conclude that government policy on mobility could influence the number of confirmed cases. To achieve this goal, we first perform a permutation test for independence.Sample correlation is used to summarize the linear relationship between two variables

For Swedish and India, we test the correlation between stringency index and confirmed cases as well as stringency index and mobility.
The null hypothesis is: (1) Stringency index and number of confirmed cases are independent.(2)Stringency index and mobility(recreation/residual) are independent.

We first perform test for independence on Sweden.

## [1] 0

Stringency index v.s. residual index

## [1] 0

Stringency index v.s. recreation index

## [1] 0

All three tests shows the p-value to be 0, we could reject the hypothesis(1)(2) that stringency index and confirmed cases as well as stringency index and mobility are independent at 5% significance level.
The same tests are performed on India, which also results in p-values of 0. The detailed code is in the appendix files.

Therefore,we reach the conclusion that for both countries, stringency index is correlated to confirmed number of people and mobility in some ways. We will explore the relationship in the next section.

Bootstrap

The assumptions of bootstrap includes:

  1. \(T \approx θ\): n is large enough so that the estimator can be assumed to be close to the true value.

  2. \(\hat F \approx F\): n is large enough so that the empirical CDF can be assumed to be close to the true CDF.

  3. \(F^* \approx F\): B is large enough so that the CDF of the bootstrap samples can be assumed to be close to the true CDF.

In this case, n=367 and B is set to be 1000. Thus, the assumptions are met and bootstrap can be used.

Here we use 3 bootstrap methods: 1 Non-Parametric and 2 Parametric.

Particularly, we would like to explore: (1)\[H_0: \text{the recreation index is positive correlated to stringency index}\] (2)\[H_0: \text{the residential index is positive correlated to stringency index}\]

The 95% confidence interval of the relationship coeficient \(\beta_1\) for India is [-1.065, -0.9397]. We reject the null hypothesis1 at significance level \(\alpha = 0.025\).

The 95% confidence interval of the relationship coeficient \(\beta_1\) for India is [0.2688118,0.3148629]. We accept the null hypothesis2 at significance level \(\alpha = 0.025\).

Thus, we may conclude that, the mobility is correlated to the stringency index, and whether it is positively or negatively related depend on which kind of index. The raise up of government stringency do help to limit the mobility of people, therefore we could see a decline in recreation and an increase in residual index followed by the government policy of keeping social distance, since more people prefer to stay indoors.

Moreover, for different countries, the levels of impact of government policy are different. Generally speaking, government stringency has more significant impact on the mobility of people in India than in Sweden.

V. Discussion

In this project, we explored the impact of government policy on people’s mobility over the control of COVID-19 pandemic. By using the daily data including stringency index, confirmed cases population mobility, we researched over these three sets of data. We completed the following tasks:

- We generated smoothed stringency index density distribution of 190 countries we obtained when their confirmed cases exceed 5,500,5000. The plots help us to get a better idea of how the strictness of government policies evolve with the increase in confirmed cases. Generally speaking, more countries believe stricter policies on mobility will help overcome the pandemic.
- We did bootstrap test over Sweden and India samples to compare the stringency index, mobility index including recreation index and residential index. By visualizing the result, we see that India posed a stricter government policy, and their mobility is relatively weak.<br>
- We did independence test for the relation between stringency index and confirmed cases, stringency index and mobility index including recreation index and residential index. We could reject the hypothesis that confirmed cases is independent of stringency, and mobility is independent of stringency on a 95% confidence level.
- We explore "how the Stringency Index affects growth rate of confirmed cases" using four methods based on the checking of assumptions: Linear Regression, Non-Parametric Bootstrap and 2 Parametric Bootstraps. We find that Larger Stringency Index can effectively decrease the growth rate of confirmed cases but can also have reverse impacts. This provides some thoughts include: 1. It is needed to adopt a strategy suited to the country’s context; 2. Though controlled mobility can help overcome pandemics, other issues cannot be ignored; 3. Investment and preparations in the health system, and relief measures need to be considered. 
- We did linear regression to explore the relation between mobility(recreation and residential index) and stringency index. We find that recreation index is positively related to stringency index on 95% confidence leve, while residential index is negatively related to stringency index on 95% confidence level.

Now here comes the questions:

India put forward very strict policies on people’s mobility. (After its confirmed cases exceeds 5 (2020-03-02), its stringency index increases rapidly and within 20 days, the index increases from 10.19 to near 100.) On the contrary, Sweden has much less strict policies than India.

As controlled mobility will decrease contact and thus impose a positive affect on reducing confirmed case growth rate, then why high stringency index in India actually may sometimes increase the growth rate under the circumstances where the mobility has been successfully controlled?

After searching more information, this might because:

The strict lockdown policy adopted by India has the following problems: 1. Adopting a strict lockdown strategy not suited to the Indian context; 2. The focus is most on mobility control, while other issues are ignored; 3. Insufficient investment and preparations in the health system, and lack of relief measures.

Specifically, about 95% of workers in India are informal and have no legal protection and also little social protection. The strict and sudden lockdown brought severe economic distress to these workers. However, there are also very little relief from the government. The total amount of additional public spending announced at the end of May is only about 1% of GDP, and most of it has not reached people; after 1 month of the lockdown, the majority (96%) did not receive food rations or cash relief from the government. This economic distress made people more vulnerable to health problems. Further, about one third of the urban population and at least a quarter of the rural population live in very crowded conditions in India, and the “stay at home” policy in this condition are even counterproductive. Access to clean water and daily necessities is inherently limited, and the strict bans have made the situation worse. In the early stage of the epidemic, India directly applied the strict lockdown policy, regardless of its own national conditions. When the economy and livelihood made the lockdown strategy unsustainable, it was forced to unlock when the epidemic became much more dangerous. (Jayati, 2020)

In the future, we might want to explore the problem over how government policy influence a pandemic. As for methods, in our projects we only use linear regression to test the relation between mobility and stringency index. Actually, we could perform Monte Carlo hypothesis test and bootstrap method to do this as well. Furthermore, we could implement some predictions based on stochastic process for the disease. As for data, we may look at other countries, and may explore other conditions of India that affect how their government policy work.
